  "output": "## Performance Analysis ‚Äî jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraping pipeline (no JS/React anywhere ‚Äî no `package.json`, no `.jsx/.tsx` files), so the \"React re-renders\" category doesn't apply. I focused on the four applicable categories, ranked by impact. `sources.yaml` currently configures **108 companies**, several with `max_pages` of 30‚Äì40 (Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix can each return hundreds of listings), so a single run can push several thousand `Job` objects through this pipeline ‚Äî the store and filter hot paths matter.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern ‚Äî `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job fetched this run, `diff()` issues one `SELECT`, then one `INSERT`/`UPDATE`, all in a Python loop ‚Äî classic N+1, and it's the biggest win here since it runs once per job, every run:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nWith thousands of jobs, that's thousands of round trips to SQLite instead of a handful. Fix: pull existing hashes for the whole batch in one query, diff in Python, then apply writes with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(self.conn.execute(q, chunk).fetchall())\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = existing.get(job.key)\n        if row is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            insert_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif row != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n            update_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ...)\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", update_rows)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                               [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n(`existing.update(...)` above assumes `conn.row_factory` is dropped to plain tuples for that query, or map `dict(cur.execute(...).fetchall())` after `SELECT key, content_hash` ‚Äî adjust to taste.)\n\n### 2. Redundant computation ‚Äî `filters.py:11-27` (`_compile` runs per job, not per run)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` recompiles the include/exclude regex patterns **from scratch on every call**:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every job!\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # same here\n```\n\nFor N jobs this is N regex-compilation passes instead of one. Fix: compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass the compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=(), exclude=(), locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n### 3. Redundant computation ‚Äî `models.py:66-75` (`content_hash`/`key` recomputed)\n\n`Job.key` and `Job.content_hash` are plain `@property`s (sha256 + string join), recomputed on every access. In `Store.diff()`, `job.content_hash` is computed once for the comparison (`store.py:67`) and then again inside `to_row()` (`models.py:75`) when building the insert/update row ‚Äî two SHA-256 hashes per new/changed job for no reason. `job.key` is similarly recomputed 2-3x per job (`diff`'s lookup, `to_row`, the `UPDATE ... WHERE key=?` branch).\n\nSince `Job` uses `slots=True`, `functools.cached_property` won't work directly, but you can compute both once in `__post_init__` and store as real slots, or simplest ‚Äî compute `content_hash` once in `diff()` and thread it through instead of recomputing inside `to_row()`:\n\n```python\n# models.py\ndef to_row(self, content_hash: str | None = None) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)\n    d[\"key\"] = self.key\n    d[\"content_hash\"] = content_hash if content_hash is not None else self.content_hash\n    return d\n```\n\nLow-severity (sha256 on a short string is cheap), but free to fix while touching `diff()` for finding #1.\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity ‚Äî fetchers do full unconditional re-fetches every run\n\n`notify.py`'s Twilio commit message and `fetchers.py`'s pagination loops (`fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, etc.) show this runs on a **12-hour schedule** (per `6ae8083`). Every run re-fetches every page of every one of 108 sources from scratch ‚Äî no `ETag`/`If-None-Match`/`Last-Modified` conditional requests anywhere in `_request()` (`fetchers.py:31-47`). Boards like Greenhouse/Ashby/Lever support conditional GETs. Adding a per-source cache of the last `ETag`/`Last-Modified` (persisted in the existing `meta` table via `get_meta`/`set_meta`) would let unchanged boards short-circuit on a `304` instead of paying full pagination + parse cost every 12 hours:\n\n```python\nasync def _get_json_cached(client, url, store, cache_key, **kw):\n    headers = dict(kw.pop(\"headers\", {}))\n    if etag := store.get_meta(f\"etag:{cache_key}\"):\n        headers[\"If-None-Match\"] = etag\n    r = await _request(client, url, headers=headers, **kw)\n    if r.status_code == 304:\n        return None  # caller keeps previous result / skips\n    if etag := r.headers.get(\"ETag\"):\n        store.set_meta(f\"etag:{cache_key}\", etag)\n    return r.json()\n```\n\nThis is more invasive (touches the fetcher signature to plumb `Store` through), so treat it as a follow-up rather than a quick win ‚Äî but it's the only real \"wasted network + CPU work\" left once #1‚Äì#3 are fixed, given the fixed 12h cron cadence.\n\n### 5. Memory leaks ‚Äî none found\n\nThis is a short-lived CLI process per run (`cli.py` / `pipeline.run_sync`), not a long-running server, so classic leak patterns (growing caches, unreleased listeners) don't really apply. Resource handling is correct: `httpx.AsyncClient` is closed in a `finally` when owned (`fetchers.py:783-787`), `Store` is used as a context manager everywhere (`pipeline.py:42`, `agent.py:54-55`) and closes its sqlite connection on exit. The only unbounded-growth concern is `jobs.db` itself accumulating rows forever (no TTL/pruning of stale postings), which is a data-retention question, not a leak.\n\n### Priority order\n1. **`Store.diff` N+1** ‚Äî biggest win, scales with total jobs fetched (potentially thousands per run).\n2. **`filters.py` regex recompilation** ‚Äî cheap fix, same N-per-run scaling.\n3. **`content_hash`/`key` double-computation** ‚Äî trivial, bundle into the `diff()` rewrite.\n4. **HTTP conditional caching** ‚Äî bigger lift, worth a follow-up given the fixed 12h schedule.\n",
